@article{Schmidt1980,
abstract = {The purpose of this study was to determine the effect of stand density, and secondarily that the shrub competition, on young western larch tree and stand development. A balanced study design included seven stand densities, and two shrub competition conditions at four locations in western Montana. This report covers 10 years of growth response. Treees were age 7 and 9 when the study was started. Crowns, stem diameters, heights, phenology, and mortality were measured at the outset of the study and 5 and 10 years later. Crown length, width, configuration, and volume of this intolerant species were sensitive to stand density -- the heavier the density the smaller the crowns in every dimension. Stem diameters were very sensitive to stand density but growth of crop trees -- was essentially the same when spaceings were wide and sites were not fully occupied. At narrow spacings, intertree competition distributed growth over the entire stand and average tree diameters declined. Height growth of crop trees was about the same on all stand densities except in unthinned stands where it was reduced about 15 percent. Densest stands produced the most basal area and volume but also the most mortality. Phenological timing was little affected by stand densitity. The removal of major shrubs at the beginning of the study had no significant effect on larch tree and stand development.},
